{"title_page": "Blue Mosque, Yerevan", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Blue Mosque (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n|building_name         = Blue Mosque\n|image                 = File:\u0544\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569 \u00ab\u053f\u0561\u057a\u0578\u0582\u0575\u057f\u00bb (\u0533\u0575\u0578\u0575 \u0574\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569), ArmAg.jpg\n|image_size            = 275px\n|caption               = An aerial view of the mosque's dome and minaret \n|coordinates           = {{coord|40.1781|44.5056|display=inline,title}}\n|location              = 12 [[Mashtots Avenue]], [[Yerevan]], Armenia<ref name=\"arlis\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Noble|first1=John|last2=Kohn|first2=Michael|last3=Systermans|first3=Danielle|title=Georgia, Armenia & Azerbaijan|date=2008|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]]|isbn=9781741044775|page=[https://books.google.am/books?id=A6yYWC2QtZUC&pg=PA154&lpg=PA154&dq=yerevan+blue+mosque 154]}}</ref>\n|religious_affiliation = [[Islam]]\n|rite                  = [[Twelver Shia]]\n|consecration_year     =\n|status                = [[Mosque]]\n|leadership            = \n|website               =\n|architect             =\n|architecture_type     = \n|architecture_style    = [[Persian architecture|Persian]]\n|facade_direction      =\n|year_completed        = 1765\u20131766\n|construction_cost     =\n|capacity              =\n|length                =\n|width                 =\n|width_nave            =\n|height_max            =\n|dome_quantity         = 1\n|dome_height_outer     =\n|dome_height_inner     =\n|minaret_quantity      = 1\n|minaret_height        = {{convert|24|m}}{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}}{{sfn|Markossian|2002|p=44}}\n|materials             =\n}}\n\nThe '''Blue Mosque''' ({{lang-az|G\u00f6y M\u0259scid}}) is an 18th-century [[Shia Islam|Shia]] mosque in [[Yerevan]], [[Armenia]]. It was commissioned by Huseyn Ali Khan, the [[Erivan Khanate|khan of Erivan]]. It is one of the oldest extant structures in [[Kentron District|central Yerevan]] and the most significant structure from the city's [[Iranian Armenia (1502\u20131828)|Iranian period]]. It was the largest of the eight mosques of Yerevan in the 19th century and is today the only active mosque in Armenia.\n\nThe mosque was secularized in the 1920s and housed the [[History Museum of Yerevan]] for more than five decades. Following Armenia's independence, the mosque was renovated with the support from the Iranian government and again started operating as a mosque, serving the Iranians residing in Yerevan.\n\n==Names==\nWestern visitors in the Russian period, such as [[H. F. B. Lynch]] and [[Luigi Villari]], referred to the mosque as G\u00f6k Jami (Gok Djami, {{lang-tr|G\u00f6k Cami}}),{{sfn|Lynch|1901|p=213}}{{sfn|Villari|1906|p=224}}{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}}<ref name=\"Ritter\"/> which translates from Turkish as [[sky blue]] mosque.<ref name=\"Kiesling\"/> It is known as \u053f\u0561\u057a\u0578\u0582\u0575\u057f \u0574\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569, ''Kapuyt mzkit\u2019'' \"Blue Mosque\" in Armenian, although \u0533\u0575\u0578\u0575 \u0574\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569, ''Gyoy mzkit\u055b'' is sometimes used as well.<ref name=\"arlis\"/> It is known in Persian as ''Masjid-i Juma'' or ''Jami-i Shahr''.<ref name=\"Ritter\"/>{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}}\n\n==History==\n{| class=\"infobox\"\n|-\n|colspan=2 style=\"background:#D3D3D3; color:black\"|<center>'''Muslims in Yerevan'''</center>\n|-\n! style=\"width: 50px\"|<center>Year</center>\n! style=\"width: 70px\"|<center>%</center>\n|-\n| 1830<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0535\u0580\u0587\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0562\u0576\u0561\u056f\u0579\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0577\u0561\u0580\u056a\u0568\u0576\u0569\u0561\u0581\u0568 1824-1914 \u0569\u0569. |url=https://yhm.am/archives/68 |website=yhm.am |publisher=[[Yerevan History Museum]] |language=hy |date=9 September 2011 |quote=\u0531\u0572\u0578\u0582\u057d\u0561\u056f\u056b\u0581 \u0565\u0580\u0587\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0567, \u0578\u0580 \u0569\u0561\u0569\u0561\u0580\u0576\u0565\u0580\u0568 /\u0576\u056f\u0561\u057f\u056b \u0561\u057c\u0576\u057e\u0561\u056e \u0574\u0561\u0570\u0574\u0565\u0564\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u0562\u0576\u0561\u056f\u0579\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0568/ \u0563\u0565\u0580\u0561\u056f\u0577\u057c\u0565\u056c \u0565\u0576` 7331 \u0574\u0561\u0580\u0564, \u056b\u057d\u056f \u0570\u0561\u0575\u0565\u0580\u056b \u0569\u056b\u057e\u0568 \u0583\u0578\u0584\u0580 \u0567\u0580 /\u0562\u0578\u0577\u0561\u0576\u0565\u0580\u056b \u0570\u0565\u057f \u0574\u056b\u0561\u057d\u056b\u0576` 4132/,}}</ref> ||<center>64%</center>\n|-\n| 1897<ref>Based on native language. The total include those who spoke Caucasian Tatar (Azeri), Persian, Kurdish, and Turkish.{{cite web |title=\u0420\u0430\u0441\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u043e \u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0443 \u0438 \u0443\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043c |url=http://www.demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/emp_lan_97_uezd.php?reg=570 |website=demoscope.ru |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502151332/http://www.demoscope.ru/weekly/ssp/emp_lan_97_uezd.php?reg=570 |archivedate=8 September 2019 |language=ru}}</ref> ||<center>43%</center>\n|-\n| 1926<ref>Turkics and Kurds. {{cite web |title=\u0421\u0421\u0420 \u0410\u0420\u041c\u0415\u041d\u0418\u042f (1926 \u0433.) |url=http://www.ethno-kavkaz.narod.ru/rnarmenia.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502132418/http://www.ethno-kavkaz.narod.ru/rnarmenia.html |archivedate=8 September 2019 |language=ru}}</ref> ||<center>7.8%</center>\n|-\n|}\n[[Image:Eriwan G\u00f6k Jami (Foto Sarre MIK Pl 9088).jpg|thumb|The Blue Mosque in Yerevan, view from the courtyard towards the prayer hall (photo F. Sarre, 1897)]]\n[[File:\u0533\u0578\u0575 \u0574\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569\u0568 (1917).jpg|thumb|The Blue Mosque by [[Panos Terlemezian]], 1917]]\n\n===Early history===\nThe mosque was built in 1765\u20131766 ([[Islamic calendar|AH]] 1179){{efn|Alternatively given as 1767-1768 (AH 1181) by [[Markus Ritter]] \"as evidenced by the inscriptions of the main ''[[mihrab]]''.<ref name=\"Ritter\"/>}} by Hussein (Hoseyn) Ali Khan, the ruler of the [[Erivan Khanate]] under [[Afsharid dynasty|Afsharid Persia]],{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}}<ref name=\"arlis\"/> as the city's main [[Friday mosque]].<ref name=\"Kiesling\"/> The mosque underwent substantial redecoration with [[tile]]s around 1887-88 (AH 1305), under [[Erivan Governorate|Russian administration]].<ref name=\"Ritter\"/> The mosque underwent another reconstruction in 1907\u20131910.<ref name=\"yerevanmasjed.ir\"/>\n\nThe mosque was the largest of the eight mosques operating in Yerevan when the Russians [[Capture of Erivan|captured it in 1827]].<ref name=\"Kiesling\"/>{{sfn|Lynch|1901|p=213}}<ref name=\"Kiesling\"/>\n\n[[H. F. B. Lynch]], who visited Erivan in 1890s, wrote: \"There is nothing very remarkable in the architecture of the mosque; but the floral paintings which adorn the ceiling of a companion and smaller edifice on the north side of the court are of very high merit.\"{{sfn|Lynch|1901|p=214}} [[Luigi Villari]], an Italian diplomat and historian, gave a detailed description of the mosque in his 1906 book titled ''Fire and Sword in the Caucasus''. He wrote that the \"great mosque called the Gok Djami [...] is a good deal more than a mosque; it is a long quadrangle containing several places of worship and a number of cells, schools, and offices of the Moslem religious administration. It is not very ancient [...] but it is handsome.\"{{sfn|Villari|1906|p=224}} The ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]]'' (1911) described the mosque as the \"finest building in the city.\"<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Erivan_(town)|short=x}}</ref> The minaret of the mosque, standing at {{convert|24|m}} was the tallest structure in 19th century Yerevan.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=297}}\n\n===Soviet period===\nThe mosque was [[secular]]ized after [[Soviet Armenia|Soviet rule]] was established in Armenia. The mosque's entrances and exits were modified significantly. The main gate, on the southern side, to the right of the [[minaret]] was blocked. The western gate was \"incorporated into a residence complex and became hardly recognizable as an entrance.\" The entrance on the northern side became the only entrance. It is accessible and visible from [[Mashtots Avenue]].{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=297}} Beginning with [[Alexander Tamanian]]'s 1924 master plan for Yerevan, the mosque has been situated more than two meters below the street level, which requires visitors to descend a flight of steps.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=299}}\n\nThe mosque ceased to operate as a religious institution in the mid-1920s. Its courtyard became a \"creative space for Armenian artists, writers, poets, and intelligentsia, facilitating the production of a new cultural and aesthetic order for socialist Armenia. The courtyard was protected by large [[elm]] and [[Platanus|plane]] trees, and in this way provided the hot and dusty city with a shaded refuge.\"{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=297}} The courtyard housed a [[teahouse]], which became a hub for intellectual gatherings. [[Yeghishe Charents]], [[Martiros Saryan]], [[Aksel Bakunts]] were among its regular visitors. Foreign guests included Armenian-American writer [[William Saroyan]], Russian Jewish poet [[Osip Mandelstam]], Russian novelist [[Andrei Bely]] and others. Local artists used the \"courtyard for exhibitions and as a laboratory for new socialist spirituality.\"{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=298}}\n\nIn the 1930s first the Anti-Religious Museum and subsequently the Museum of [[Antifascism]] were housed at the mosque. From 1936 until the collapse of the Soviet Union, the mosque housed the Museum of Natural Sciences, which included a [[planetarium]] inside the main prayer hall and the [[Yerevan History Museum]].{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=299}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Historical Overview |url=https://yhm.am/?lang=en |website=yhm.am |publisher=[[Yerevan History Museum]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907194644/https://yhm.am/?lang=en |archivedate=7 September 2019 |quote=In 1936 it was moved to the Blue Mosque (Gyoy Djami) where it functioned for about 56 years.}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Blue Mosque in Yerevan.jpg|thumb|The main entrance of the mosque from [[Mashtots Avenue]].]]\n\n===Independence period===\nIn the late 1980s, during the [[Nagorno-Karabakh conflict]], the mosque did not sustain any damages because it was considered to be Persian, not Azerbaijani, and housed the city's history museum.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=299}}\n\nIn February 1991 a preliminary agreement was reached between the city's authorities and an Iranian delegation to restore the mosque.<ref name=\"FBIS\"/> The mosque underwent major renovation between 1994 and 1998.<ref name=\"arlis\"/> The city's authorities officially transferred the right to use the mosque to Iran on October 13, 1995.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=294}} The government of Iran allocated some 1 billion [[Iranian rial]]s (over $1 million) for restoration works.{{sfn|Markossian|2002|p=45}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Visiting Iranian Minister Comments on Relations|journal=Daily Report: Central Eurasia|date=16 October 1995|pp=[https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pur1.32754080840915&view=1up&seq=94 87\u201388]|publisher=[[Foreign Broadcast Information Service]]|quote=\"Blue Mosque is the only large Iranian memorial which was preserved even under conditions of mass termination of churches in the 30s\" Hakob Movsesi said. Iranian Government allocates some 1 billion Iranian rials for capital restoration of the mosque. Restored mosque will become the center of Iranian culture in Yerevan.}} [https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pur1.32754080840915&view=1up&seq=94 online] ([https://ia601504.us.archive.org/35/items/visitingiranianministercommentsonrelations/png2pdf.pdf archived])</ref> The mosque was re-opened as a religious institution in 1996.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=299}} [[Brady Kiesling]] described the restoration as \"structurally necessary but aesthetically ambiguous.\"<ref name=\"Kiesling\"/>\n\nAnother reconstruction was done between 2009 and 2011.<ref name=\"yerevanmasjed.ir\"/>\n\n[[File:Erevan - La Mosqu\u00e9e bleue 01.JPG|thumb|The courtyard and the dome.]]\n\n====Today====\nThe Blue Mosque is the only active mosque in [[Yerevan]] and all of Armenia,<ref name=\"Aghajanian\"/><ref name=\"Brooke\"/> which has a small Muslim population (between 812<ref>{{cite web |title=\u053f\u0580\u0578\u0576\u0561\u056f\u0561\u0576 \u056f\u0561\u0566\u0574\u0568 \u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574 [Armenia's religious makeup] |url=https://ampop.am/followers-of-different-religions-in-armenia/ |website=ampop.am |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190907105433/https://ampop.am/followers-of-different-religions-in-armenia/ |archivedate=7 September 2019 |language=hy |date=27 December 2017 |quote=\u0540\u0561\u0575\u0561\u057d\u057f\u0561\u0576\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0562\u0576\u0561\u056f\u057e\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0567 812 \u0574\u0578\u0582\u057d\u0578\u0582\u056c\u0574\u0561\u0576...}}</ref> and 1,000 or 0.03% of the total population).<ref>{{Citation|editor-last=Miller |editor-first=Tracy |date=October 2009 |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |page=28|title=Mapping the Global Muslim Population: A Report on the Size and Distribution of the World's Muslim Population |url=http://pewforum.org/newassets/images/reports/Muslimpopulation/Muslimpopulation.pdf |accessdate=2009-10-08 |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091010050756/http://pewforum.org/newassets/images/reports/Muslimpopulation/Muslimpopulation.pdf |archivedate=2009-10-10 }}</ref>\n\nSince restoration, it has become a religious and cultural center for the Iranians residing in Armenia and Iranian tourists visiting Armenia.<ref name=\"Aghajanian\"/> In 2003 [[Thomas de Waal]] noted that the only regular worshippers at the mosque were \"the dozen or so diplomats from the Iranian Embassy.\"{{sfn|de Waal|2003|p=74}} Less than a decade later, in 2009, ''[[ArmeniaNow]]'' wrote that of the up to 2,000 Iranians residing in Yerevan as many as 500 periodically attend the mosque on Thursdays.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ionesyan|first1=Karine|title=Mourning rite at Blue Mosque: Iranians in Yerevan pay tribute to their compatriots|url=https://www.armenianow.com/news/10262/mourning_rite_at_blue_mosque_irani|work=[[ArmeniaNow]]|date=17 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Iranian cultural center inside the mosque complex attracts young Armenians seeking to learn [[Persian language|Persian]].{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=303}} The Persian library of over 8,000 items, named after the poet [[Hafez]], was opened inside the complex in October 2014.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=302}}\n\nOn December 10, 2015 the government of Armenia leased the mosque complex to the embassy of Iran to Armenia for 99 years to use it as a cultural center.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u053b\u0580\u0561\u0576\u056b \u0564\u0565\u057d\u057a\u0561\u0576\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0568 99 \u057f\u0561\u0580\u0578\u057e \u0561\u0576\u0570\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0575\u0581 \u056f\u0585\u0563\u057f\u0561\u0563\u0578\u0580\u056e\u056b \u053f\u0561\u057a\u0578\u0582\u0575\u057f \u0574\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569\u0576 \u0578\u0582 \u0570\u0561\u0580\u0561\u056f\u056b\u0581 \u0570\u0578\u0572\u0561\u0574\u0561\u057d\u0568 |url=https://hetq.am/hy/article/64411 |work=[[Hetq]] |date=10 December 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908060535/https://hetq.am/hy/article/64411 |archivedate=8 September 2019 |language=hy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0540\u0540 \u053f\u0561\u057c\u0561\u057e\u0561\u0580\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0561\u0576 \u0578\u0580\u0578\u0577\u0578\u0582\u0574 \u0578\u0580\u057a\u0565\u057d \u0576\u057e\u056b\u0580\u0561\u057f\u057e\u0578\u0582\u0569\u0575\u0578\u0582\u0576 \u0570\u0578\u0572\u0561\u0574\u0561\u057d \u0568\u0576\u0564\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0565\u056c\u0578\u0582 \u0587 \"\u053f\u0561\u057a\u0578\u0582\u0575\u057f\" \u0574\u0566\u056f\u056b\u0569\u00bb \u0570\u0578\u0582\u0577\u0561\u0580\u0571\u0561\u0576\u0576 \u0561\u0576\u0570\u0561\u057f\u0578\u0582\u0575\u0581 \u0585\u0563\u057f\u0561\u0563\u0578\u0580\u056e\u0574\u0561\u0576 \u056b\u0580\u0561\u057e\u0578\u0582\u0576\u0584\u0578\u057e \u0570\u0561\u0576\u0571\u0576\u0565\u056c\u0578\u0582 \u0574\u0561\u057d\u056b\u0576 \u0578\u0580\u0578\u0577\u0578\u0582\u0574 |url=https://www.e-gov.am/gov-decrees/item/26700/ |website=e-gov.am |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190908060637/https://www.e-gov.am/gov-decrees/item/26700/ |archivedate=8 September 2019 |language=hy}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Blue Mosque Yerevan Dome.JPG|thumb|Closer view of the dome]]\n[[File:2014 Erywa\u0144, B\u0142\u0119kitny Meczet (10).jpg|thumb|The minaret]]\n\n==Architecture==\nThe mosque is listed by the Armenian government as a monument of national significance.<ref name=\"arlis\"/> It is \"one of the oldest buildings in central Yerevan\"{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}} and the \"only extant building of the Iranian period in Yerevan.\"<ref name=\"Ritter\"/> [[Markus Ritter]] described it as the \"main model for the early Qajar mosque architecture of the Iranian period.\"{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=297}} The mosque complex covers an area of {{convert|7000|m2}}.{{sfn|Markossian|2002|p=44}} The mosque itself is {{convert|97x66|m|ft}},<ref name=\"yerevanmasjed.ir\"/> while the courtyard is {{convert|70x47|m|ft}}.<ref name=\"Ritter\"/> The mosque contains the traditional [[Shia]] attributes, including a [[minaret]], three [[mihrab]]s (prayer halls), holy inscriptions, etc.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=300}} The mosque includes 24 arched cells that face the pool in the middle of the courtyard, which is surrounded by a rose garden.{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}} The minaret, standing at {{convert|24|m}} tall,{{sfn|Markossian|2002|p=44}}{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=296}} has a 7-degree slope, but is considered to be architecturally safe.<ref name=\"yerevanmasjed.ir\"/>\n\n==Efforts to list as a World Heritage Site==\n[[File:ArmenianStamps-393.jpg|thumb|A 2007 Armenian stamp depicting the mosque.]]\n{{see also|List of World Heritage Sites in Armenia}}\n\nIn October 2007 Armenian Foreign Affairs Minister [[Vartan Oskanian]] stated during his speech at the 34th session of the [[UNESCO]] General Conference in Paris that the Blue Mosque and other sites are on the waiting list for inclusion in the UNESCO World Heritage List.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vartan Oskanian's Speech to UNESCO General Conference|url=http://asbarez.com/56025/vartan-oskanians-speech-to-unesco-general-conference/|work=[[Asbarez]]|agency=via [[Armradio]]|date=19 October 2007}}</ref> In January 2013 Armenian Minister of Culture Hasmik Poghosyan stated that Armenia will take all possible steps for inclusion of the mosque in the UNESCO list of [[World Heritage Sites]].<ref name=\"armenpress 2013\">{{cite news|title=Involvement of Blue Mosque in UNESCO list of cultural heritage is highly significant|url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/704871/involvement-of-blue-mosque-in-unesco-list-of-cultural-heritage-is-highly-significant.html|agency=[[Armenpress]]|date=14 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Armenia applies to place Blue Mosque on UNESCO's World Heritage List|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151221033541/http://www.todayszaman.com/world_armenia-applies-to-place-blue-mosque-on-unescos-world-heritage-list_304799.html|work=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=22 January 2013}}</ref> She reaffirmed this position in a meeting with Iranian Culture Minister [[Mohammad Hosseini (politician)|Mohammad Hosseini]] in April 2013. Hosseini stated that he hoped Armenian efforts would succeed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Armenia will apply to include Yerevan's Blue Mosque in UNESCO World Heritage Site|url=https://news.am/eng/news/149639.html|work=news.am|date=19 April 2013}}</ref> Armenia's Foreign Affairs Minister [[Eduard Nalbandyan]], in his speech at the 38th session of UNESCO General Conference in November 2015:<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by Edward Nalbandian, Minister of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Armenia, at the 38th session of UNESCO General Conference|url=http://mfa.am/en/speeches/item/2015/11/06/min_unesco_speech/|publisher=Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Armenia|date=6 November 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote frame|...neighboring Iran has made great efforts to preserve and protect the Armenian cultural heritage. The [[Armenian Monastic Ensembles of Iran]], the oldest of which dates back to the 7th century, were inscribed on the World Heritage List by the Iranian Government. On our part, Armenia reconstructed the Iranian 18th century Blue Mosque in Yerevan, and is going to inscribe it on the World Heritage List.}}\nOn October 15, 2015 Armenian Prime Minister [[Hovik Abrahamyan]] and First Vice President of Iran [[Eshaq Jahangiri]] attended an event dedicated to the 250th anniversary of the mosque.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ghazanchyan|first1=Siranush|title=Iran's First Vice-President visits Blue Mosque in Yerevan|url=http://www.armradio.am/en/2015/10/15/irans-first-vice-preside-visits-blue-mosque-in-yerevan/|agency=[[Public Radio of Armenia]]|date=15 October 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219162032/http://www.armradio.am/en/2015/10/15/irans-first-vice-preside-visits-blue-mosque-in-yerevan/|archivedate=19 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iran's high-ranking delegation attends 250th anniversary celebration of Yerevan Blue Mosque foundation|url=https://armenpress.am/eng/news/822272/irans-high-ranking-delegation-attends-250th-anniversary-celebration-of-yerevan-blue-mosque-foundation.html|agency=[[Armenpress]]|date=15 October 2015}}</ref> Abrahamyan stated in his speech that both Armenia and Iran \"are now making efforts to have it put on the UNESCO World Heritage list.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=PM Attends Blue Mosque Foundation 250th Anniversary Celebration in Yerevan|url=http://www.gov.am/en/news/item/8143/|agency=Government of the Republic of Armenia|date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nArmenian and some Western sources refer to the mosque as Iranian/Persian.{{efn|For instance, [[Armenpress]], the state news agency, calls it the \"Iranian Blue Mosque of Yerevan\" in a 2013 article.<ref name=\"armenpress 2013\"/>}}<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kaeter|first1=Margaret|title=The Caucasian Republics|date=2004|publisher=[[Infobase Publishing|Facts on File]]|isbn=9780816052684|page=[https://books.google.am/books?id=DHCVPqlsmvgC&pg=PA12&dq=yerevan+blue+mosque 12]|quote=The Blue Mosque [...] is the only Persian mosque in Yerevan still preserved.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Carpenter|first1=C.|title=World and Its Peoples, Volume 1|chapter=Yerevan|date=2006|publisher=[[Marshall Cavendish]]|isbn=9780761475712|page=[https://books.google.am/books?id=j894miuOqc4C&pg=PA775&dq=Blue+Mosque+%5B...%5D+is+the+only+Persian+mosque 775]|quote=...only one large Persian mosque, the eighteenth-century Blue Mosque, is still open, now renovated as a cultural center.}}</ref><ref name=\"Brooke\"/> In fact, it is often referred to locally as simply the \"Persian mosque\".{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=299}} [[Tsypylma Darieva]] notes that \"in local media and in official discourses, the Blue Mosque has been strongly associated with the new expatriate political body symbolizing the recent Armenian\u2013Iranian friendship. This dominant reading of the place defines the Blue Mosque exclusively as the \u2018Persian Mosque\u2019.\"{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=299}}\n\n[[Thomas de Waal]] argues in his 2003 book ''[[Black Garden]]'' that \"when the Armenians refer to the 'Persian mosque' in Yerevan, that name obscures the fact that most of the worshippers there, when it was built in the 1760s, would have been, in effect, Azerbaijanis.\"{{sfn|de Waal|2003|p=80}} According to Darieva it served as a [[Friday mosque]] for \"Yerevan\u2019s Muslim (mostly Azeri-speaking) population, until the middle of the 1920s.\"{{sfn|Darieva|2016|p=297}}\n\nIn Azerbaijan, the mosque is usually referred to as a monument of Azerbaijani heritage of Yerevan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Armenian gov't to allocate Yerevan Blue Mosque to Iran for 99 years Zoom|url=http://en.apa.az/azerbaijan_religion_news/armenian-gov-t-to-allocate-yerevan-blue-mosque-to-iran-for-99-years.html|agency=[[Azerbaijan Press Agency]]|quote=Note that, Blue Mosque belonged to the Azerbaijanis who once lived in Yerevan.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Blue Mosque, historical Azerbaijani monument in Yerevan - PHOTOS|url=http://www.today.az/news/society/79534.html|work=today.az|date=17 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Zeynalov|first1=Natiq|title=Yerevanda G\u00f6y m\u0259scid h\u0259r g\u00fcn \u0130ran v\u0259t\u0259nda\u015flar\u0131 il\u0259 dolu olur|url=http://www.azadliq.org/content/article/2032531.html|work=azadliq.org|agency=[[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]|date=5 May 2010|language=az|quote=Halbuki, onun fikrinc\u0259, bu, Az\u0259rbaycan m\u0259d\u0259niyy\u0259tinin bir abid\u0259sidir.}}</ref> One government official called it \"the largest religious center of Azerbaijanis living in Yerevan.\"<ref>Sayyad Salahli, First Deputy Chairman of the Azerbaijani [[State Committee for Work with Religious Organizations (Azerbaijan)|State Committee for Work with Religious Organizations]]. {{cite news|last1=Dada\u015fov|first1=Valeh|title=State Committee official: 'Lease of Blue Mosque to Iran has preconceived purpose'|url=https://report.az/en/religion/first-deputy-chairman-of-state-committee-lease-of-blue-mosque-to-iran-has-preconceived-purpose/|work=report.az|date=15 December 2015}}</ref> A 2007 book titled ''War against Azerbaijan: Targeting Cultural Heritage'', published by the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Azerbaijan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Azerbaijan]] and the [[Heydar Aliyev Foundation]], objected to the restoration of the mosque in the 1990s and to its \"presentation as a Persian mosque.\"<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Imranly|editor1-first=Kamala|title=War against Azerbaijan: Targeting Cultural Heritage|date=2007|publisher=[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Azerbaijan)|Ministry of Foreign Affairs of Azerbaijan]] and [[Heydar Aliyev Foundation]]|location=Baku|isbn=978-9952-8091-4-5|url=https://www.history.az/pdf.php?item_id=20100816124447313&ext=pdf|p=313|quote=The Goy mosque was turned into the Museum of History of Yerevan in the Soviet period, and then 'restored' and presented as a Persian mosque after 1991.}}</ref> [[Rouben Galichian]] argues in his 2009 book ''Invention of History'':<ref>{{cite book|last=Galichian|first=Rouben|authorlink=Rouben Galichian|title=The Invention of History: Azerbaijan, Armenia and the Showcasing of Imagination|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217143857/http://roubengalichian.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/8-InventionOfHistory_Eng_book.pdf|date=2010|orig-year=2009|edition=2nd|publisher=[[Gomidas Institute]]|location=London|isbn=978-1-903656-88-4|p=66}}</ref>\n{{Quote frame|It must be said that all mosques built [in Yerevan] between the 1635 and 1820s were erected by the Iranians and bearing in mind that the local Muslim population, as well as the Persians were both Shias, their mosques were identical. Hence, it is very difficult to understand how the Blue Mosque could be an \u201cAzeri\u201d mosque, since such a classification did not exist.|align=center}}\n\n{{Commons category|Blue Mosque, Yerevan}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Islam in Armenia]]\n* [[Persian Armenia]]\n* [[Abbas Mirza Mosque, Yerevan]]\n* [[Shah Abbas Mosque, Yerevan]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n;Citaions\n{{reflist|3|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Kiesling\">{{cite book|last=Kiesling|first=Brady|authorlink=Brady Kiesling|title=Rediscovering Armenia: An Archaeological/Touristic Gazetteer and Map Set for the Historical Monuments of Armenia|date=2000|location=Yerevan/