s presidential election in New Hampshire\n| previous_year = 1936\n| next_election = 1944 United States presidential election in New Hampshire\n| next_year = 1944\n| election_date = November 5, 1940\n| image_size = 150px\n| image1 = FDRoosevelt1938.png \n| nominee1 = '''[[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'''\n| party1 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| running_mate1 = '''[[Henry A. Wallace]]'''\n| electoral_vote1 = '''4'''\n| popular_vote1 = '''125,292'''\n| percentage1 = '''53.22%''' \n| image2 = WendellWillkie.png\n| nominee2 = [[Wendell Willkie]]\n| party2 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Indiana]]\n| running_mate2 = [[Charles L. McNary]]\n| electoral_vote2 = 0\n| popular_vote2 = 110,127\n| percentage2 = 46.78%\n| map_image =\n| map_size =\n| map_caption =\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n| before_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n| after_party = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{ElectionsNH}}\nThe '''1940 United States presidential election in New Hampshire''' took place on November 5, 1940. All contemporary 48 states were part of the [[1940 United States presidential election]]. State voters chose 4  electors to the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]], which selected the [[President of the United States|president]] and [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]].\n\n[[United States presidential elections in New Hampshire|New Hampshire]] was won by incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], who was running against [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] businessman [[Wendell Willkie]] of [[Indiana]]. Roosevelt ran with [[Henry A. Wallace]] of [[Iowa]] as his running mate, and Willkie ran with [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Charles L. McNary]] of [[Oregon]].\n\nRoosevelt won New Hampshire by 6.44%, at the time the best performance by a Democrat in this traditionally Republican state since the latter party was founded, and since bettered only by [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Lyndon Johnson]] in [[1964 United States presidential election in New Hampshire|1964]] and [[Barack Obama]] in [[2008 United States presidential election in New Hampshire|2008]].<ref>Dave Leip\u2019s Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections; [http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/compare.php?year=1940&fips=33&f=1&off=0&elect=0&type=state Presidential General Election Results Comparison \u2013 New Hampshire]</ref> This was also the first time that a Democratic presidential candidate since [[Franklin Pierce]] in [[1852 United States presidential election in New Hampshire|1852]] won an absolute majority of the vote. Roosevelt\u2019s gain in New Hampshire and other New England states, in an election when Willkie carried almost seven hundred counties that the President had won during his landslide four years beforehand, was due to support in the region for helping Britain and France during [[World War II]].<ref>Menendez, Albert J.; ''The Geography of Presidential Elections in the United States, 1868-2004'', pp. 67-68 {{ISBN|0786422173}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n{{Election box runningmate begin | title=1940 United States presidential election in New Hampshire<ref name=results>{{cite web|title=1940 Presidential General Election Results \u2013 New Hampshire|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/state.php?year=1940&fips=33&f=1&off=0&elect=0|publisher=U.S. Election Atlas|accessdate=23 December 2013}}</ref>}}\n {{Election box US candidate with party link|\n   |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n   |candidate  = '''[[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]]'''\n   |homestate  = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n   |vp_name    = '''[[Henry Agard Wallace]]'''\n   |vp_state   = [[Iowa]]\n   |votes      = '''125,292'''\n   |percentage = '''53.22%'''\n   |ev         = '''4'''\n   |evprct     = '''100.00%'''\n}}\n  {{